abstract: Sam Dagher’s “Assad or We Burn the Country” describes a regime that will go to any length to stay in power.

abstract: The painter Jordan Casteel discusses her favorite artwork and the affinity she feels for its creator.
snippet: The painter Jordan Casteel discusses her favorite artwork and the affinity she feels for its creator.
lead_paragraph: When the painter Jordan Casteel first saw a copy of “Alice Neel: Painted Truths,” a book on the 20th-century painter Alice Neel, she was struck by the artist’s “freshness and sense of imperfection.” “I found myself totally in awe that there was somebody who had made work in a way that I was trying to make work myself,” she says. “Her work emulates and speaks and lusts out with a sense of humanity that I really admired, and was drawn to.”

abstract: In “Last Day,” Domenica Ruta braids together the stories of a teenage girl, a tattoo artist, three astronauts and a young woman who hears voices.

abstract: The British author turns his attention to the subterranean world with “Underland.”
snippet: The British author turns his attention to the subterranean world with “Underland.”
lead_paragraph: CAMBRIDGE, England — Robert Macfarlane was partway up a mountain in Scotland when a fellow climber decided to lighten the mood by reciting some William Carlos Williams: “The descent beckons / as the ascent beckoned.”
